we regularly review our real estate loans for impairment using both quantitative and qualitative factors, such as debt service coverage and loan-to-value ratios. we evaluate a real estate loan for impairment when the most recent valuation reflects a projected loan-to-value ratio at maturity in excess of 100%, even if the loan is currently paying in accordance with its contractual terms.
of our $3.9 billion of impaired loans at real estate at december 31, 2013, $3.6 billion are currently paying in accordance with the contractual terms of the loan and are typically loans where the borrower has adequate debt service coverage to meet contractual interest obligations. impaired loans at cll primarily represent senior secured lending positions.
our impaired loan balance at december 31, 2013 and 2012, classified by the method used to measure impairment was as follows.
